              <otmi:snippet>Across the continent, from Zimbabwe to Sudan, China is winning friends by lending money to Africa&apos;s most unsavoury regimes without asking awkward questions</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>And the Sudanese government lacks the political infrastructure — and probably the political will — to enforce proper safeguards</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>As a News story on page 393 of this issue illustrates, scientists and engineers are sometimes complicit with this process</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But South Africa, with its wealth and its relatively sophisticated political system, is an exception</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But that doesn&apos;t mean that large dams need to be built</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But there is no reason why both needs can&apos;t be met</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>By the start of the First World War, almost all of the continent had been taken by European powers</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>China is willing to invest, in part to cement closer ties with an important oil producer</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>China seems to have no such qualms</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Chinese firms and government agencies will operate with few checks or balances</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Hydropower certainly has a role to play in Africa&apos;s development</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In many other African nations, there is little chance of proper safeguards being implemented</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>It says that funders such as the World Bank make things too complicated</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Lahmeyer International, the German company that is coordinating the project, is disarmingly open about why this is so</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Most of the continent&apos;s available hydropower resources are untapped and could, if properly harnessed, provide a valuable and renewable source of energy</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Smaller projects can be run with more input from local people and are easier to combine with other renewable sources, such as solar power</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>So, once again, thousands of poor people look set to suffer so that a big dam project can go ahead</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>South Africa has, to its credit, tried to incorporate some of these lessons into a hydropower and water-supply project in Lesotho</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Studies of how to resettle 50,000 people whose land will be flooded, and assessments of the project&apos;s environmental impact, were finished late in the day, and undertaken with insufficient rigour</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Successful projects in Asia and South America have shown that small hydropower projects can supply a few thousand local people without the need for big resettlement projects</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Sudan&apos;s Merowe dam on the Nile could be set to repeat the mistakes that have characterized previous large-scale hydropower projects in poor countries</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The G8 nations — correctly, if belatedly — are considering how best to invest in Africa, so that the previous misappropriation and mismanagement can be avoided</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The project is imperfect, but at least its administrators have sought to consult with local people and to run independent assessments of its environmental impact</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The project&apos;s backers have sought to portray Merowe as a necessary trade-off between the competing needs of development and the rights of local people</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The rights of Africa&apos;s own people, who lost land and many lives during this process, drew scant attention</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The same goes for the European companies involved in Merowe and elsewhere</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The staff and shareholders of these firms are part of another scramble for Africa, in which local peoples&apos; rights and needs are once again being sidelined in the stampede for wealth.</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>They know that rigorous political consultation and environmental assessment are needed if big dam projects are to succeed</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>They would have stopped the project going ahead if the World Bank, for example, was funding it</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Thorough environmental and social impact assessments take years; Sudan wants power now</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Towards the end of nineteenth century, Europe suddenly woke up to the riches that lay in the vast unexplored continent to its south, and the &quot;scramble for Africa&quot; began</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Unless the lessons of the past are thoroughly learned, large dam projects will sink over time in a morass of corruption, haphazard displacement of local people, lack of political accountability, and failure to plan properly for maintenance</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Why recall this episode today? Fleetingly, last summer, Africa was big news, when it became the central topic at a meeting in Scotland of the leaders of the G8 group of top industrialized nations, chaired by British prime minister Tony Blair</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Yet the real action is being taken by a donor nation that isn&apos;t even a member of the G8: China</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Yet they have been happy to engage in such projects in the absence of any such safeguards</otmi:snippet>
